<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> Species of this alliance, informally called dune mat, inhabit the inner dunes inland from the leading edge of the beach. Species composition is richer on the inner dunes than on the leading edge because salt spray is less, and these areas are rarely impacted by saltwater overwash during storms. The sand is reflective and mobile when dry, and it creates high insolation and temperatures in full sunlight. Plants can be damaged by sand blast, root exposure, and foliage burial under shifting sand. Beach sand has a low capacity to retain water and is nutrient-poor with little organic matter. Deep sands may remain moist, receiving and storing water, while the surface sand stays dry much of the time. Summer fogs ameliorate surface conditions to some degree (Pickart and Barbour 2007). <br/>
<br/>
Plants of the dune mat are well adapted to these conditions. Most are perennial herbs with rhizomes and fibrous roots that can exploit surface and deep sources of water. Plants are capable of very rapid growth in response to burial and grow longer shoots when buried. Seed germination occurs in the spring when the sand is wet. Surviving the summer dry period is the critical stage in the plants’ life cycles (Barbour and Johnson 1977). <br/>
<br/>
Species dominance shifts both temporally and spatially as a result of environmental conditions. In some areas, local mound-by-mound dominance of <i>Abronia latifolia, Ambrosia chamissonis, Poa douglasii, </i>and other species suggests fine-scale microsite patterning; however, the scale of disturbance and the clonal mat-forming characteristics of many of the major species suggest that stands should be considered on a larger spatial scale. For these reasons, we present this alliance broadly and describe this variation at the association level. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
