    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af, Ah-l). Stands exist at Salinas River State Beach in Monterey Co. (Bluestone 1981), at Morro Bay in San Luis Obispo Co. (Williams and Potter 1972, Williams 1985), between Morro Bay and Point Arena (Casavecchia and Biondi 2001), at Monterey Peninsula (McBride and Stone 1976), and between Morro Bay and Point Reyes (Pickart and Barbour 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-b, Ad-e, Ag-l). An early account of the Del Norte and Humboldt Cos. dunes is found in Burtt-Davy (1902); more recent accounts exist for dunes at or near Humboldt Bay (Duebendorfer 1989, Johnson 1963, Parker 1974, Pickart 1987) and for those at Point Reyes National Seashore and environs (Holton and Johnson 1979, Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a). Stands exist on dunes at Manchester State Park in Mendocino Co. (CNPS unpublished survey data 2020).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-d, Bf-j). Couch (1914) provided a historic account of dunes at Manhattan Beach in Los Angles Co., where dunes closest to the ocean were dominated by <i>Ambrosia chamissonis,</i> and inland ones were dominated by <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> and dune mat plants. Johnson and Rodriguez (2001) reported on stands from the northern Channel Islands, and Junak et al. (2007) denoted stands from the Channel Islands that included insular endemics. CNPS (2005) included data from Santa Catalina Island.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Much recent interest in the state’s dune ecology has focused on non-native species that have changed vegetation dynamics on the dunes (Pickart and Sawyer 1998). In northern California, <i>Ammophila arenaria, Carpobrotus </i>spp., and <i>Lupinus arboreus </i>(which is believed to be naturalized north of Sonoma Co.) are being managed to restore native-dominated stands and enhance populations of CNPS list 1B plants, including <i>Abronia umbellata</i> var. <i>breviflora, Erysimum menziesii </i>, and <i>Layia carnosa </i>(Kaye 2003, Pickart et al. 1989, Skinner and Pavlik 1994). Many other rare and localized herbs occur in the dune mat alliance, including <i>Agrostis blasdalei, Chorizanthe cuspidata </i>var<i>. villosa, Gilia capitata </i>ssp<i>. chamissonis, Gilia millefoliata, Leptosiphon rosaceus, Lupinus tidestromii, </i>and <i>Monardella undulata, </i>among others. </div>
</div>

    

    

